# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Watermark Vault – Caddyfile (example / template)
#
# This file shows how to set up Caddy as a reverse proxy so that:
#
#   1. The main application is served at your primary domain.
#   2. Each tenant can use their own custom domain (e.g. book.myphotobusiness.com)
#      that maps to the main Watermark Vault instance while showing only that
#      tenant's booking page.
#
# Prerequisites
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   • Caddy 2.x  (https://caddyserver.com)
#   • The Watermark Vault server is running on port 3001  (Express / Node)
#   • The Watermark Vault frontend is built and served on port 5066  (nginx)
#     or alternatively, the Express server serves the static files itself.
#   • For each tenant custom domain the tenant's DNS record must point
#     to this server (A / CNAME).
#
# How custom domains work
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   1. Super-admin sets a tenant's custom domain in the Platform → Tenants
#      panel of the admin UI  (e.g. "book.myphotobusiness.com").
#   2. The tenant (or their DNS provider) adds an A or CNAME record pointing
#      that domain to this server's public IP.
#   3. Caddy automatically provisions a TLS certificate for the domain via
#      ACME / Let's Encrypt.
#   4. When a visitor opens https://book.myphotobusiness.com the React app
#      calls /api/tenant/by-domain?domain=book.myphotobusiness.com, resolves
#      the tenant slug, and renders that tenant's booking page — all at the
#      custom URL.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ── Option A: named domains ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# List every custom tenant domain explicitly. Caddy will obtain a TLS cert for
# each one automatically.

# Main application domain
app.example.com {
    # Forward API requests to the Node/Express backend
    reverse_proxy /api/* localhost:3001

    # Forward everything else to the built React frontend served by nginx
    reverse_proxy localhost:5066
}

# Tenant custom domain – Jane Smith Photography
book.janesmithphotography.com {
    reverse_proxy /api/* localhost:3001
    reverse_proxy localhost:5066
}

# Tenant custom domain – another tenant
photos.acmestudios.com {
    reverse_proxy /api/* localhost:3001
    reverse_proxy localhost:5066
}


# ── Option B: on-demand TLS (wildcard / dynamic) ─────────────────────────────
# Use this block to accept ANY domain that resolves to this server and
# automatically provision TLS certificates on first request.
# This means you never need to restart Caddy when adding a new tenant domain.
#
# ⚠ Requires Caddy to be compiled with the on_demand_tls module (default in
#   the official binary) and a reachable ACME endpoint.  See:
#   https://caddyserver.com/docs/automatic-https#on-demand-tls
#
# Uncomment the block below to use on-demand TLS instead of Option A:

# {
#     on_demand_tls {
#         # Optional: whitelist endpoint so only known tenant domains get certs.
#         # The endpoint should return HTTP 200 for allowed domains, 4xx otherwise.
#         # ask http://localhost:3001/api/caddy/verify-domain
#     }
# }
#
# :443 {
#     tls {
#         on_demand
#     }
#     reverse_proxy /api/* localhost:3001
#     reverse_proxy localhost:5066
# }


# ── Optional: domain-verification endpoint helper ─────────────────────────────
# If using on-demand TLS with `ask`, the server exposes:
#   GET /api/caddy/verify-domain?domain=<hostname>
#   → 200 OK if a tenant with that customDomain exists and is active
#   → 404   otherwise
# This prevents Caddy from minting certs for arbitrary domains.
# See server/index.js for the implementation.
